Definition

A Spring Bean is an object that is created, configured, and managed by the Spring IoC container.

Key Points

Managed by ApplicationContext

Defined via annotations, Java config, or XML

Supports dependency injection

Lifecycle managed by Spring

2Ô∏è‚É£ Bean Scopes
Definition

Bean scope defines how many instances of a bean are created and how long they live.

Types & Key Points

singleton (default) ‚Äì one instance per container

prototype ‚Äì new instance each request

request ‚Äì one per HTTP request

session ‚Äì one per HTTP session

application ‚Äì one per ServletContext
‚ö†Ô∏è Scope ‚â† thread safety

3Ô∏è‚É£ Bean Lifecycle
Definition
The bean lifecycle describes the creation ‚Üí initialization ‚Üí usage ‚Üí destruction of a bean.

Key Points
Instantiation
Dependency Injection
Initialization (@PostConstruct)
Ready to use
Destruction (@PreDestroy)
Destroy not called for prototype beans

4Ô∏è‚É£ Autowiring
Definition
Autowiring allows Spring to automatically inject dependencies into beans.
Key Points
Types: constructor, setter, field
Constructor injection is recommended
@Qualifier resolves multiple bean conflicts
Reduces boilerplate code

5Ô∏è‚É£ Spring Annotations
Definition
Annotations are metadata used to configure Spring behavior.

Key Points (Common Annotations)
@Component, @Service, @Repository
@Controller, @RestController
@Autowired, @Qualifier
@Configuration, @Bean
@Value

